caption: Amazing khachapuri! Great food and great  value for money

Dishes are unique in the sense that they have a homey feel but with a Georgian twist! Quickly becoming one of my favorite restaurants!
Looking forward to coming here again. Close to authentic Georgian food experience, for more authentic you probably need to go to some Georgian aul 👍🏻

We had never tried Georgian Food.  Our son suggested this place as he and his girlfriend loved the place  I would say I am glad they recommended the place.  The food was just down right good.  The appetizer had just the write hint of turmeric and I had never eaten a Marigold flower but I must say it definitely added some pizazz to the flavor of the dish. We had made reservations as I don't think you would get a table on a Saturday night with one.  They give you a 2 hour timeslot and that is your time.  I can respect that these days with the limitation on seating with Covid.  Their Covid protocol was good and made me feel safe  The Server was attentive and served us well.   As you can see by the photos the food was just down right good.
Treat yourself to a broad sampling of appetizers for a wide variety of Georgian food.     The pickled beet was a personal favorite. Food is authentically planned and executed.
Great job w distancing and sanitation. Great ambiance, cocktails are yummy!  Excellent service and the food is terrific! Definitely a spot not to be missed.
Delicious food and in good proportions! Great ambience and customer service.
Great food. Authentic and very flavourful.
One my favorite Georgian restaurants, incredible food and service. I recommend trying some of the different Georgian wines.
Delicious food, great ambiance & attentive staff. Would definitely recommend for a date night or a small friends gathering since there are a bunch of shareable plates
Came for Restaurant Week 2021 and it was fabulous!

We got take out food for restaurant week 2021, and it was perfect. Curbside pickup was easy and the order was ready in time, all the staff were helpful and following COVID precautions of mask wearing and social distancing. Everything was exactly as we ordered and was delicious. It was my first time having Georgian food and I will definitely be returning to dine in once it is safe to do so.
The best georgian food in DC area!
Delicious food, very comfortable outdoor patio despite frigid temperatures. Would absolutely go back, very garlicky and flavorful food.

Fantastic evening at Supra! The outdoor dining experience is very pleasant and comfortable, with individual heat lamps for each table. The service was delightful, very attentive and personable. Last but not least, everything we selected from the menu was delicious: the eggplant rolls stuffed with walnut-garlic paste, the corn fritters, the cornmeal and sulguni fritter served with a lemon-mint yogurt, the soup dumplings filled with cheese & fresh mint... The Newfangled Georgian Old-Fashioned was also a winner!
Everything was very good. A little overpriced for the amount so 4/5 but will return. We tried the ajaruli, lyulya kebab, and eggplant nigvzit. Recommend them all.

Ordered takeout from here, and were very happy with our meal. The Khachapuri was delicious (even when we had to heat it back up a little bit). The lamb kabob was tender and juicy, and the mushroom's were flavorful and full of cheese. We would love to come and do a full meal here once they reopen indoor dining!
Khachapuri is really tasty, but the star of the show for me is the stuffed eggplant appetizer. Or maybe the walnut cake. Doesn’t matter, try it all!

Absolutely wonderful! If you’re unfamiliar with Georgian food start with the ajaruli (cheese bread) and then go for  the khinkali kalakuri

I have never had a bad meal at Supra and it’s a spot I often take friends from out of town when they’re visiting. Their khachapuri (flaming cheese boat) is great but where I think they really excel is in their vegetarian dishes like their beets or their cauliflower. That said, khachapuri may be the best leftover food in the world to come home to after having a few drinks at the bars.

The atmosphere is very chic and the food is certainly novel (I had never had Georgian food before), albeit not cheap given the modest portions. The biggest negative was the service, which was extremely slow.
Who would have guessed that Georgian food is so delicious?!?! Get a bunch of the sharing plates! The cauliflower was amazing! Ajaruli...OMG so delish! And very interesting wines...the list goes on...
Great Georgian place in DC. Wish there were more food like this in DVM area
Food tastes like in Georgia, very authentic.

I had previously been there and had a good experience but this time around I can't say I did. The menu was quite limited. Not sure if its COVID related or what the reason is. But irrespective of that the food was quite ordinary and also several menu items weren't available.
Great food
Very disappointed with the adjarian khachapuri - badly shaped, cold with too much mozzarella cheese.

Not sure what happened with the staff at Supra... I used to come very often and was super happy both with the food and the service. Tonight I came to pick up an order my wife had made online. I went to the bar and kindly asked about my order, the bartender started shouting at me that he was too busy with other stuff. After I asked why he was upset and whether I should talk to someone else, he went to check on my order and said I should come back in 6min. I came back 10min later and this time, a woman as rude as the bartender asked me to wait and finally brought my order after I waited inside next to two full tables of loudly laughing maskless clients... the bar was also exceptionally dirty with empty bottles here and there. Nothing I was used to at Supra... very disappointing.
Food was awesome.  Service was great.

We was wisiting this place last year , hachapuri was great but hinkali was not like it shoud be ,we was there today and hinkali was really good ,kindzmarauli also like always great , i think need some small education  for new costumers how to it this delicious food
This was our 4th visit and it wasn’t as pleasant.  A lot of new staff with less experience.

Excellent service starting from the moment of calling for a reservation. In-door and outdoor patio is available. Atmosphere is cozy, friendly with a lot of light. The smell from the open kitchen made us can't wait to explore the menu.Soko Ketse was recommended and surprised how they can make this dish with such a simple mushroom to be so tasty. Ajapsandali (eggplants) dish would be completed if there were some kind of bread tag along. Ajaruli- the boat shape khachapuri is the highlight of the brunch. The Duck Dirty Rice is a love too although for me I think it could have been more flavorful but don't take my standard as this is my first time having it. Pork-beef soup dumpling ( Kalakuri) is something I recommend you to try as well. If you end up having a full belly already, just take it home and microwave it still tastes as good.  One thing they need to seriously fix is the fly problem. I sat indoor and often get bugged by fly and fruit fry in which the only excuse I could give to them was that the front door is opened?... still, that was not cool.  However, overall, It was a relaxing Saturday afternoon brunch. Please don't be in a hurry to leave if you come here, take your time to enjoy the food/drinks and relax otherwise you might get upset as the service can be slow on weekends.

I had an immensely sleezy end to my evening here. So sleezy I have to give this place one star. A person in my party ordered a dish that required bread. As all the complimentary table bread had been consumed by the time his dish arrived and it came with no bread on it's own,(Which is surpsing. The dish should be prepared for the customer, not the customer prepared for the dish) we asked for more bread. Keep in mind, this is restaurant week and our meals are $35 per plus we ordered a $60 bottle of wine. He waited. Unable to eat his appetizer. So I asked again. He waited some more and our entree arrived. As we were finishing up that I asked again. "He can't eat this if he doesn't have bread," I added. A man, I presume to be the manager, came over and advised the bread was made to order and was in the oven. He didn't seem pleased at all btw. Definitely with the tone of "I'm being extra." Fine. But, also these are the dishes you set up for restaurant week? How can you serve a dish that absolutely needs bread and A LOT of it but not have any on hand.  I didn't say this, but still he was a bit curt to me. Finally the bread arrived just before dessert. We get the check. They charged us for the bread! I waved over a staff and pointed this out. She said, "You receive two bread for restaurant week and you ordered one extra." I said, "No, I asked for bread three times, but we only received two breads." She then said without missing a beat, " You receive one bread for restaurant week, but then you ordered one more." You're going to lie to me right there! For $3! Like literally change what you just said to my face without blinking. I couldn't believe it. But I'm not going to fight with someone over $3 there. I'll do it here. That was a gross end to our evening. A. You were rude to me when I'm trying to ensure a pleasant evening for my shy guest. He's looking at me forlorned all evening because I guess you expected us to make sure he kept a ration of what was already a tiny portion of bread for 4 people for his appetizer??? B. You obviously desperately needed to hit me back in some way over the bread because it didn't matter how many breads we received, you just needed to make sure you charged me for it. Essentially, hey, I'm just there to have a good evening. It's you who came back with two unnecessarily emotional responses over something so petty. Mature a little.
Supra is amazing. Everything is so delicious and the wines are fantastic
Great traditional Georgian food. Classy atmosphere. The back bar is a great place for a casual date.
Excellent Georgian food. I’m not exactly sure what all I ordered was but it was delicious!
Outdoor seating very comfortable, attentive service, tasty food! Very careful about cleanliness of table and seats between customers
Wow! Ambiance. Love the decor. Great venue for party or HH. Must have the cheese egg Khachapuri!!!!!

delicious food and great service.  I can't even imagine running a business  like this in a pandemic, but supra did well: outside distanced seating, indoor dining for the brave, good take out.  A few of suggestions that would take my review to 5 stars: - please, don't use reusable menus; switch to one-time paper menus instead or QR code menus - please, put a sanitizer bottle on each table - please, switch to contactless payment

I do not ever post reviews, but I found this specific incident to be one of the most horrific treatments of verbal assault that I've ever experienced from a restaurant employee who is supposed to be representing a restaurant during a time when the food industry is particularly vulnerable. My partner called Supra on Sunday, July 5th at 9pm to simply ask about a possession that may have been left there a while back. When asked, the woman who my partner spoke with immediately laughed and was condescending. She said "it's been X amount of time" and did not bother to check. As my partner politely said "thank you" and proceeded to ask if they are open for outdoor seating (because we would like to support their business), she hung up the phone. We called back to express that it was very condescending and rude the way she addressed the missing possession, but also CONTINUED to ask about their status of the restaurant because we have been returning customers. She immediately shouted "you have no idea what I've been going through today" and again stated how it was ridiculous that we were calling about the missing possession, while still not addressing the status of operations. We were honestly speechless and shocked by the verbal assault she delivered, and we explained that we were simply customers and verbally should not have the burden of being the victim of a restaurant representative's "bad day". She then aggressively blamed her demeanor on the restaurant's position during COVID-19. This is absolutely not the way to treat customers during COVID. We asked to speak to a different person because she was not entertaining any questions, but she stated she was a manager. We asked for her name and she said "I don't have to give you my name" and continued having a manic episode over the phone. We eventually ended the call in frustration after getting an answer about their operating status, but it was without reason because we will not be taking the risk of supporting a restaurant that has verbally assaulted us, when we can easily support other local businesses that make us feel good as consumers. Driving customers away during a time when the restaurant industry is fragile is extremely hurtful to the restaurant and has absolutely resulted in losing us as loyal customers. This story will be shared widely, because no customer deserves to be verbally assaulted for simply asking if there was a possession left behind. We are extremely heartbroken because we've adored this restaurant since moving to DC, and as someone in the restaurant industry myself, I feel hurt that we cannot ethically support the business.

I never post negative reviews, but I felt compelled to after the way I was just treated by a staff member at Surpra. I left a possession of mine at the restaurant a while back, but due to the COVID-19 pandemic, I haven't been able to go in person to retrieve it. I called this evening around 9 pm EST  to see if they still have it and spoke to a "manager," who scoffed at my question, laughed, and said "there's no way we would have that at this point, it's been months" in a such a condescending tone. She then hung up before I could ask her a follow-up question so I called back and I explained how I found her tone uncalled for and unacceptable. She then began to lecture me on how I had "no idea what she was going through today" and that I had "no right to be upset with her tone." I asked to speak to a manager to which she responded "I am the manager." I then asked for her name to which she replied, "I don't need to give you that." I informed her I would seek out how to get in touch with her supervisor and she responded, "good luck!" I honestly have never had such a negative, belittling, and dismissive interaction in my life with someone. This saddens me because I love Supra and am a loyal, returning customer, but I honestly am not sure I can ever return after this incident.
Never had Georgian cuisine. The waiter was very helpful with suggestions and the food was amazing. If you are of the legal drinking age, try the Chacha. Take it easy though, it's powerful stuff.

Excellent customer service. Food is great and delivered timely. Very accommodating given the current COVID and social distancing issues. Staff were super friendly and helpful. I will be a repeat customer.

I've been here a few times, and it's always been delicious, but last night I did the 'Supra at home' and it was amazing! The instructions were pretty much fool-proof, and everything is portioned out so there's no guesswork. It's worth every penny, and there are definitely leftovers today.

My first time at Supra; ordered take out for my graduation from grad school. Service was great, food was absolutely incredible. And they gave me a gift for my graduation - thank you so much for making it a special celebration even during the COVID19 health crisis.
This place is a gem! Fried chicken sandwich is quick and delicious for lunch
Ajaruli khatchapuri, beet salad, sulguni cheese, and kindzmaruli wine!

Bery good ..!

Great food and ambiance. If you want to get a good taste of Georgian food and wine, give it a try. You'd need a reservation, but if you don't have one you can sit at the bar which is what we did and enjoyed.
Great food and service.  Party of 15.

Love it.  What can I say about a bread boat of cheese. It tastes as amazing as it sounds and I will happily eat 3 of these. They serve it with a pat of butter and an egg yolk that the server mixes in the bread boat for you and then you dig in. The bread tasted fresh and covered in melted cheese.... yum.  The eggplant was a bit of a surprise; rather than tasting like eggplant it tasted mostly like the nutty mixture that was inside the wrap. An interesting taste that I liked but wasn’t my favorite part of the meal.  THIS. FISH. We never managed to get the name of the fish but we polished it off as cleanly as you could with a fork. Super tender with crispy grilled skin and served with a bunch of greens and a pomegranate sauce this was a highlight of the meal for sure. The fish wasn’t fishy at all and frankly tasted great on its own but the salad definitely added another layer of flavor. We preferred to eat it without the sauce but the sauce itself was very interesting! Savory and sweet it wasn’t like anything we’ve ever had before.  Dessert was also amazing. Sweet and tart all at once with a texture that felt like a slightly grainier jello? I’m not selling it very well but trust me it was great.  The atmosphere was good! It was fairly spacious and we didn’t feel too close to other tables. It has the modern vibe that a like of mid-upper class places in DC tend to have. The service was good, our server explained the dishes well to us when we asked and had the information memorized and understood very well. There was a period where he disappeared for 10 minutes when we wanted the check but sometimes nature calls so I’ll give him the benefit of the doubt. It can be quite loud but that could also just be the other diners we unfortunately had next to us that day.
I loved the place and the food is excellent

A must visit restaurant in DC! Amazing food, and great service. The hot appetizers: potatoes and cauliflowers were yum. The mushroom dumplings were scrumptious (my favorite at this restaurant). We got the trufeleta for dessert, which was easily consumed after a full meal. Simply delish! Would come back.

I visited Supra for lunch and am excited to enjoy again! The menu was full of cold and warm starters, delicious soups,  soup dumplings and much more. The food was tasty, filling and reasonably priced.  The environment was warm and welcoming, full of plants and mirrors. They even have a small shop where you can purchase books, ornate salt and pepper shakers, etc. Highly recommend!
Great food!

Had a great experience! Went for brunch with a small group and really liked the warm atmosphere. Service was fast and attentive and the food was first rate. This place came recommended to us, and so I'm passing along the recommendation to you. Give it a try. You won't be disappointed.
Great wines, dumplings, everything really. Try a chilled Goergian amber. The roasted cauliflower in walnut sauce was great. Lots of veggie options.
It's great to finally have a Georgian restaurant in DC! The menu has all of the Georgian classics plus a great wine selection. Prices as well as happy hour are on par for DC.
Great service, food and ambiance.
food was absolutely phenomenal!

Wonderful Georgian food and wines! Good service. Bring a large party so you can sample everything. The dumplings are similar to a Chinese meat bun. The different stuffings certainly results in a delicious unique flavor. Unfortunately, they do not allow you to wear the wigs at the table anymore.....
I have been to Supra four times now, pretty much every time I’m in town. Fantastic food. Great for large groups.

Everything is good here, you can’t go wrong. I especially love the extensive wine list and how amazing the staff is about teaching you about Georgian wines, and letting you sample a few options to find one (or ahem, more than one) you really love. Can’t wait to go back.

You must book here to get table service  We didn’t and had to sit at the bar which was ok.  They serve the same menu at the bar and bar area as the main restaurant.  Food came out fairly quickly apart from one dish which I think they may have forgotten about but the bar lady ended up chasing it up for us.  Easy to find but if you want to enjoy and have a fairly nice meal best to book ahead.
Great service with delicious reasonably sized and priced portions to share with the whole gang.

Had such aa fabulous meal here the other day. Came with a friend who had never had Georgian food, and he's already wanting to go back. We ordered the following items:  -Eggplant Nigvzit- there are only  3 but this item  is one of my faves.  -Cauliflower Satsivi: wow this was fantastic. If you like cauliflower, you should definitely give this a try  -Ajaruli: as my friend has never had Georgian food before we had to try the original khachapuri. This is just  absolutely delicious. I would like to try some of the others, but If youve never had khachapuri before, you should get the Ajaruli.  Beef Chashushuli: absolutely delicious, especially on a cold night. This is actually the only large plate I've ever ordered. Hard to try sometjint new when this is so good.  Can't wait to go back!!

The service was terrible. We have been waiting for a while to make an order. Then waiters brought dishes not by order, first was hot dish, then appetizer, it is really unprofessional. Delicious wine, overall average food and very slow service. The first come first serve bar area feels competitive, with people beginning to sit down at a table before the other folks are even gone. I would consider giving it another try because I understand restaurant week can be intense, but the service was slow and cranky and the food about average. However, the dessert (walnut cake and gelato) and wine selection were superb.
Rapid and friendly service. Decent Khinkali and Adjaruli Khachapuri.

Food and wine was amazing as always BUT our appetizers and entrees arrived almost simultaneously. We explain to the waiter the situation and she understood, saying that she was going to return the entrees to the kitchen. 30 seconds later, another waiter brought the same 2 entrees saying that the “kitchen cannot take this back”. Definitely not going to come back.
I enjoyed this place and went for their resturants menu. Food was delicious and service good and quick.
Amazing food. Great experience. Julian our waiter was awesome!
This was an amazing meal.  The service was excellent.  The food was really great.  Appetizers, entree, and desert were all just perfect.  I would eat here again any time!
So far this is my favorite restaurant in DC. The food is amazing and the staff is very friendly. Even if you don't know anything about Georgian food, this place is definitely worth a visit.
Great place and the food is excellent! It would be great if they offer lactose free dairy options for cappuccinos, etc., but otherwise loved it! Good customer service.

Best meal I've had in a long time. From the wine (nice and fruity) to the salad and large plates, everything was excellent. Georgia is geographically on the northwest border of Turkey. The food had a similar geography. It reminded me of the Turkish pides and kebabs, but the roasted chicken had flavoring that reminded me of Eastern European dumplings. The decor of the restaurant has a midcentury vibe with custom teak/walnut seating and Georgian hats hanging from the ceiling. The bathroom had Georgian vinyl records on the wall and old black and white snap shots in the hall. The servers are very knowledgeable and enthusiastic. I really loved the place. Try it. You won't regret it.
Was looking forward to trying the place. The food was authentic but on the heavy side, salty side. Recommend the tasting platter as appetizer
Nice place but just one bar. Long lines.
Delicious and very exotic foods. An expanding experience full of discoveries. Also very nice staff.

Go here. Don't waffle or second guess other choices. Just go here. Order a bunch of apps, get out of whatever comfort zone you're lurking in and find some heavenly flavors here.  Best lamb i've ever tasted in the Chakapuli, and the cheese/bread/egg in the Ajaruli is divine. Good beers and cocktails, lovely wood and stone and glass decor with some green vines etc. Big windows on the front, tons of light during the daytime.  Excellent for 3-4+ friends to lose a few hours in. Not cheap but hell if it wasn't worth it. Will revisit for the next several items on my list to experience.

Great food with a nice atmosphere.  Will definitely come back when I am in DC again.
wondreful and nice

Failed attempt at Georgian Food presented in French fine dining format (less is more) with absolutely dismal service. 5 of us drove 1.5hrs to Supra for the 1st time.  I have never walked out in the middle of service nor has I ever had Management comp my meal.   Supra did both.  If I had to break it down in stars:  Food: 2, Service: 0, Ambiance: 3.  Overall: 1  SERVICE: 25 minutes to get water.  Waiter couldn't pronounce any dishes.     Chkrhirtma was described as "it’s like American chicken soup". No Georgian wines knowledge whatsoever.  45 minutes and we asked another waiter to order at least appetizers and wine.  1hr 45min into service!!! we finished appetizers incl. the ones we were advised by 2nd waiter to double as portions are small.  We finished our wine and empty glasses were sitting at our table. Our real waiter  silently grabs our empty glasses and menus and walks.  I asked if he wants to know if we like another wine?  How about entrees?  But at this point (1hr 45min) we called the FOH manager.  Result – we left!  Manager despite my objection, did buy our meal.  So service is non-existent and you think food would make up.   Nope. FOOD...  People of Georgia in the Caucasus region, famous for its hospitality and cuisine.  More is never enough there.    Serving Georgian food French style in a tiny little portions is like ordering Lo Main at Chinese place and have 1 noodle on the plate.   Visit any one of a dozen Georgian restaurants located from Philadelphia to New York and you will see how it’s done.   Most appetizers here are very small – bite or tapas size. Exception would be a Khachapuri as it is good.  For Khachapuri I would only pick Ajaruli as a classic. Beet Themalit salad on the plate covered less than half.  Nothing special or flavorful. Eggplant Nigvzit was also small and it was sort of ok. Very special dish, Chvishtari - fritters of corn with smoked sulguni turned into a joke.   4 tasteless poppers with challenge to find cheese.  Sulguni is an excellent cheese and lemon-mint yogurt sauce could have made a difference if not for a tiny drop on the top and missing cheese. Lobia Kotanshi - too small to really figure out when all had so little of taste. I can’t review any other food as we never got to it.  So why is this the way it is at Supra.  If you note, ownership and top chefs in the kitchen are not Georgian or from Georgia.  One sous chef is, but apparently her influence is not enough to say to the rest that this is not how food is served in Georgia, people, or any other Georgian restaurants anywhere in the world.   Front Staff has no knowledge of food or wines.  Not even an attempt of properly pronouncing names.    Oh, how I would have wanted to see a non-ethnic chef produce great ethnic food.  It would truly be an accomplishment.   I know It’s been done before and I live with one as well.  But Supra misses the mark at food or service.   It’s a shame as when reading highs of management staff credentials you realize it clearly don’t mean a thing here.  Something else comical…   General Manager was telling 5 of us about 2 Michelin Stars they have at Supra.   And I have a Brooklyn Bridge for sale.  Supra has no stars.   Supra is on Bib Gourmand list of restaurants in DC.  For those not familiar, Michelin Travelers Guide designed for travelers first and then foodies.   Foodies look at stars and the rest at budget meal places and hence the category.  Finally, as I have mentioned before, order a couple of Chachapuri to-go with a bottle of Kingzmarauli or Kvnachkara wine and hit home with it.  Do not ask or consult with any staff.  This is as close as you will get to taste Georgian meal in DC today.  We actually went to another restaurant that night as we were still hungry from "huge" appetizers.   Also first one for me.   Our group consisted of Executive Chef, General Manager of the Restaurant and Bar chain,  FOH Manager of fine dining restaurant, Catering Manager.  All from different restaurants.   It is with heavy disappointment that I brought myself to even write this review.
Great restaurant. This was my first visit and I cannot wait to go back. The people were very nice and the food is excellent.  Make reservations early.  The dinning room fills quickly.

Lovely patio on the street and a welcome retreat from the flavors of 'American' food!  Food that is an adventure, a conversation and an trip around the world for sure.  There's a very cozy bar seating around the corner from the hostess too, great for meetups and dates, and you might not see it unless you're headed to the restroom already.  Great foodie spot on 11th!!!

I just want to share our experience.We were group of people, driving from Baltimore ( about an hour) to celebrate graduation friend of ours,we were very excited to check new restaurant Supra, but our excitement went down very quickly. Service was very slow and not attentive. After we arrived we were waiting Water 20 min, then to order some appetizers its took other 25 min.it was hard to get our server attention. We end it up not ordering any entres and second bottle of wine. We end it up leaving  other place, up to street and actually got fantastic service and food.this place definitely has lots of things to improve. The worst thing was the manager, who has his attitude toward us.Improvement  need to start with management. We want to wish good luck to this place.
Expensive, small portions, adjaruli not close to the real thing.  Decent service.

I’ve never been to a Georgian restaurant before.  I was not disappointed.  The orange wine list was extensive and the food was beyond expectation. Plenty of vegetarian options as well. Will be back whenever we are in the city!

We went to Supra with a group of four and the meal  did not disappoint! We made a reservation so there was no wait to get our table. We asked the staff for suggestions on how much food to order for our group and it was fairly accurate though we had some trouble finishing the Supra tasting board once the Mixed Grill platter showed up. Overall the food and atmosphere was great, service was prompt but it was at times difficult to hear our server.  Will definitely go again once I’m no longer full after this massive meal!
The place is great, the vine, the quality of the food, it is all on a top level. Highly recommend.
Pretty good Georgian food that's reasonably priced.  The service though was on the slow side and left much to be desired - though in fairness it was a very busy night.
Amazing experience and food

Truly a Georgian feast. I was a huge fan of this restaurant and I'm glad I decided to check it off my list. I already have plans to return. The staff was great our service was incredible. The food here was incredible the combinations of herbs and sauces was amazing.
Great food and service. Wonderful breads.
great food but didnt saw a supra :(
Great food. A bit noisy.
It ’s very good to eat the food for the first time. It ’s good for your friends to come here. The waiters are professional and polite. The taste of the dishes is very good.  The dishes here
Great food and service!

WOW... Georgian food, who knew? I still dream about the eggplant nigvzit which was hands down one of the most memorable dishes of 2019... the khachpuri (cheesy bread with toppings), khinkali (soup dumplings, they have a daily meat and a daily veggie option, we went with the meat ones), and a cold cucumber yogurt soup rounded out the meal. All were incredible. As was the Georgian wine. There were so many other bites and spreads that we didn't get to that I can't wait to go back and try. Also really excited for Tabla, their new sister restaurant coming to Petworth (next door to Call Your Mother!) soon-ish.  Supra truly is a gem. A wonderful, tasty, surprising gem.

I've been to quite a few restaurants in DC and this is my new favorite! My wife and I were visiting for an anniversary trip to see a concert and decided to check Supra out.  We were blown away by our experience!!!  When we came in it was happy hour and there were excellent drink specials as well as smaller sized food portions at discounted prices. We tried almost everything on the menu and both had about 3 or four drinks and everything came out to only about a hundred bucks...way more than we were thinking and planning for.  Everything was delicious.  The wines from Georgia had an excellent taste which was like nothing I've ever had.  You could taste the earthiness from the clay vessels they are stored in.  It was amazing.  All of the dishes were excellent but the Imeruli Khachapuri and the Khibizgina were my favorites.  We sat at the bar and Brandon, our bartender, was outstanding.  He provided excellent recommendations and took time to talk about the foods and wines...giving us additional background on each.  He provided outstanding service!  Finally, the music they were playing was right out of my typical playlist...including Tom Waits, Nick Cave, Portishead, The National, and many others.  I've never been to a place that actually played that kind of music.  Kudos to your DJ!  Couldn't recommend this restaurant any higher.  It is definitely our go-to spot in DC.

I think this is the best meal I have ever had! We were seated immediately when we arrived for our reservation and our service was great. The wine was amazing too. I thought it was reasonably priced for the high quality of food. I would recommend getting several small plates to try out everything. Also make sure you come hungry :-)

Unique, delicious food in a gorgeous atmosphere! I went for brunch and had the khabizgina which was incredible, and also very huge and filling (had leftovers!). I thought the decor was amazing (beautiful wood, lots of plants, etc) and made it feel like a really nice, classy experience without being stuffy. The service was great as well. I will definitely return!

The food was absolutely amazing and perfect to share with a group. Our server was attentive, helpful, charismatic and engaging.  Unfortunately, my birthday night was ruined by the aggressive, rude, and hostile manager who was on duty this evening (Juanita 11/21/19). She reacted horribly to a situation and left a very negative atmosphere in her wake. After spending over $600, she decided to berate us over a $10 grocery store cookie cake. The policy (charging $25 to cut and serve the cake) was not the problem, the manager's attitude, delivery, and demeanor was. Sadly, it was enough to make us all never want to return, nor recommend to anyone else. Hopefully in the future, a manager with over 15 years of hospitality management experience,  one who should excel in customer service and interaction, will learn how to properly interact and speak to customers.
We attended the once a month supra, with Georgian toasts and explanations of their culture. Fascinating and delicious, food for thought as well as dinner.

We, party of 6, have been in this restaurant on Saturday, November 16, 2019. I am agree with the person, who mentioned that service from waters and food runners in this place is poor. It is awful. 3 times these people brought us something what we never ordered. It looks like waters and food runners just do not know their menu. The same time we have been waiting and waiting to get one of the sups we really ordered. The food was fine, we liked it  (I should give 2 stars because of quality of food). But the choice of wines is very specific and you should not drink vines in this restaurant. So, I would not recommend this place.
As always their food was great, it was first time for me for their happy hour. HH drinks were reasonably priced, I wish food menu wasnt that limited.
Extraordinary food and service.
Wonderful dining experience. Just ask for recommendations, everything was amazing
Delicious food and great service! Will definitely return when next time in DC!
Everything wad great. Give Khingali and Pear lemonade a try.
Food was delicious!
Excellent and interesting food.  The soup dumplings were a real treat as was everything else.
Great place to visit and try Georgian cuisine The food is delicious.
Great food, friendly staff. Make the reservation before going there. It absilutly worth your time and money.

Overpriced. Was with some friends. Four times they came to say... well we are done....trying to get us out of the table. And they put more tip that what we left on the credit card. Very annoying experience.
Realllllly yummy cheese boats
Delicious. Good food. Nice service

It’s difficult to find an authentic Georgian restaurant outside of Georgia, but Supra has pulled off the feat.  The food is delicious and cooked in traditional Georgian ways.  Good selection of Georgian wines as well.  A welcome addition to the Washington dining scene, Supra brings a taste of Tbilisi to the nation’s capital.
Stellar service with detailed knowledge of the dishes. The tasting board was delicious way to sample the vweuous appetizers. Warning... Except doe the pickles, they are all scrumptious.

First time here and I would highly recommend it! Our server Max(shortened version of his name) made wonderfully delicious recommendation. The great service and incredible food made it a memorable experience.
Delicious Georgian food!
One of my favorite places to eat! The cheese boat (khachaphri) is amazing, and it’s fun to try all of the new dishes!
One of the beet restaurants in DC! Amazing food, wine, atmosphere and service. Konstantin is wonderful.

What a shame. This was really not that great. I've not had Georgian food anywhere else, but given the hype, I want to believe that this place didn't do it justice. Food was really average unfortunately, and prices eye-watering... I get that it's the dc market, but the cheapest bottle of wine at $50 is a rip-off. Plus, when asking for a recommendation, and the waiter  suggests the $80 bottle of wine without batting an eye lid, you've lost my respect. Ah, service was also pretty bad. The waiter never came to check on us and had to be constantly waived down anytime we needed anything. Given how much you pay, service really needs to up its game.
Seriously,  where else are you going to find fantastic Khachapuri?! This place is great and the staff are awesome. I absolutely hate going to DC, but will make the trip for Supra.

Very chic but sober decor with some Georgian items: A very soothing ambiance. Each dish was very elegantly presented but more importantly they all were exquisite. The staff was very attentive and friendly. They have a great affordable  three course menu for lunch. A real pleasant experience.

Easily a 'ten.' Had a company event here and everyone was just amazing at helping, accommodations, and attention. Would definitely have another business event here; no hesitation. The food though... I mean, I've never had food this good. Full disclosure, I don't have the opportunity to eat much Georgian food, but after this experience I don't think I care to try and find a better place. The chef has nailed the menu. Everything is perfect. Flavor combinations are amazing and everything is served perfectly. Must visit place for anyone interested in trying something new. Just be give enough time to park. That's a disaster. 😀

The best food I have had in a long time. Inspired by my interest in Georgian culture and cuisine, I came to this restaurant with a friend. It surpassed my expectations. Greatest restaurant I have been to all year, and I plan to go back very soon. It will become a regular part of my year going forward. My sincerest thanks to the owners and the staff for creating such an amazing atmosphere in which we can get a great taste of Georgia.
Went here for lunch. Incredible. Had the eggplant nigvzit and the spinach khachapuri. This place is very authentic and delicious. Will be back soon to try more dishes
I ate here three times in two weeks. Definitely love the food and the Georgian wines. Def coming back for more
The service was excellent. Our server was very knowledgeable.
Foods are so good.
The waiter was totally lost, we had to wait so much for our food it was a disaster. I put 10% of tip but I should have given 0%.

The $20 business lunch is a great opportunity to try some really good food at a reasonable price.  The eggplant stuffed with walnuts was a delicious appetizer.  A glass of white wine was perfect with the trout and green tomato relish.  If you're in a hurry, service is excellent and you can have lunch in an hour.  Or you can just relax and take your time to enjoy your meal.  Obviously great care was taken with the decor.  There are interesting things to look at everywhere.  You can even purchase some funky Georgian-made socks, a hat or other unusual items.  A really special place.
You will be overly full when you leave. There is nothing you can do. This is Georgian food. Live it. Love it.

We liked this place overall bc of the Georgian food and its location but the service of the dull waitress was top 3 worst we've had in the last yrs. We've had Georgian food in Prague and loved it so we decided to check this place out while visiting D.C. The outside sitting area and food were good but wouldnt go back bc of the service.

I only stopped by for a quick happy hour. Menu seemed pricey for what it is (I had just visited Georgia). I also couldn't understand why they would play very vulgar (yes, nasty swearing) Russian jazz on their speakers... especially given the overall aversion to all things Russian in general.
Great Georgian food
First time trying Georgian food. The cocktails were so good and the food was so great and flavorful! It did take a little while for my friend’s food to come out but overall a great experience.
Beautiful place if you like Georgian food! Wouldn’t say they had a “brunch” menu, but the service was great!

Good food, great atmosphere, And the best hostess I've seen in a while...  Went with a couple of mixed plates that were great, the lite wine flights were good as well, the Kachapuri are the best, both the egg and melted cheese one as well as the spinach, and on top of all pf that, the hostess would cpme and explain about every dish and every menu option.  Highly recommend.
Good food and great service. The muscles were pretty awesome and in a decently large portion despite being in the apps section.

Adding two stars because of a fast and positive response from the owner. He assured me they are working on the issues I raised. Hopefully Supra will soon have service to match the excellent food.  Simply awful service. Our party of five arrived shortly after they opened at 5 pm, so they were not at all busy. And yet we were left sitting at our table for 10 minutes, with waiters walking past us, chatting amongst themselves, completely ignoring us. I finally had to flag down a waiter, who took our order with indifference bordering on hostility. He walked away and left us sitting with our menus still in our hands. I collected the menus and sat them at the empty table next to us, which prompted a stream of waiters offering to take our order. Why not assign waiters to tables? Supra's "system" is pure chaos, and shared tips does not help with bad service. But it did not end there. The rude waiter got the khachapuri order wrong (I clearly described what I wanted even if I did not know the name of the dish), and when the wrong dish arrived, I tried to politely say "I thought I ordered the adjaruli" - to which the impertinent waiter replied with an incredulous "You think you ordered? Or do you know?" He fixed his mistake, but that was the last we saw of him - the food came, cattle car style from random runners, but no wait staff checked in on us again. I asked the last food runner to pack up the remaining khachapuri and bring the check; he acknowledged my request and then almost immediately stacked dirty plates on top of the leftover khachapuri. We waited and waited for the check. I finally had to ask the hostess / manager for the check - I explained that while the food was excellent, the service was terrible. She mumbled something like "sorry about that," but once she saw to getting the check, she wasn't the least bit interested in hearing about our experience. The evening ended for me in their filthy bathroom (at 6:30 pm - really?) with a disgusting autoflush toilet that wasn't working. And yet by the time we left, the place was full. I just read numerous reviews about the bad service going back several months, but I guess management just doesn't care as long as the food brings in customers. Well, Supra has several less customers now. I will not tolerate service like this, no matter how good the food may be.

Made a reservation on Reserve and this was my first time ever trying Georgian food and it was amazing!  Definitely get a combination of cold, hot, khachapuri (cheese-filled bread) and khinkali (soup dumplings) to get the whole experience.  FAVORITES: (Cold) EGGPLANT NIGVZIT: Eggplant stuffed with walnuts, cilantro - $7 *The eggplant was very tender and the filling was nutty and herbaceous (Cheese-Filled Bread) AJARULI: Boat-shaped cheese bread, organic egg yolk - $14 *I've had this bread before but this was by far the best khachapuri I've ever had, the cheese was salty and eggy and the bread was crispy on the outside and doughy on the inside.  I also realized that I have never  mixed the egg and cheese enough because Juanita the manager mixed it for us and it tasted so much better! (Soup Dumplings) KHINKALI: Beef/Pork Soup Dumplings (6) - $18 *Really unique experience, their selection changes daily and I loved how the process of eating this was so great!  Steamed dumplings with hot soup inside.  Yassss.  I would suggest getting 3 if you plan on getting a lot of other plates. (Dessert) YOGURT MURABIT: Panna cotta, candied cherries, black walnuts - $10 *I love panna cotta but oftentimes restaurants don't get the texture right and this was perfectly creamy and the toppings of fruit and nuts really went well with the dish.  GOOD: ELARJI - $7 *this is gonna sound weird but the interior texture reminded me of crab meat but the dish was tasty, my friend wanted these but croquettes aren't my thing BOSTNEULL TOLMA - $8 *pretty tasty for grape leaves, weren't too bitter and it was interesting with the red peppers APPLE CAKE: Gluten-free apple cake, caramelized apples, vanilla ice cream - $12 *this cake was really moist and tasty for being GF but the panna cotta was so amazing that the apple cake was overshadowed  WINE: They have an extensive wine list with a lot of skin contact wines (Qvevri) which I found a little too bitter or sour for me so I went with a rose which was fabulous!  If you don't like Qvevri wines I would suggest asking your server which ones aren't.  SERVICE: Our server was 100% on for our entire dining experience.  The manager Juanita educated us on Georgian food and made great recommendations throughout dinner.  VERDICT: Yes this restaurant will be in my regular rotation - I can't wait to come back!

Great place for gatherings, their eggs and cheese boat and tasting board are must haves here. Great restaurant to visit anytime one is in DC. Recommend it and will be my first stop there for a bite any time I am in DC

I have been here twice now. Really outstanding Georgian cuisine. Three stars because of the service... For a restaurant of its quality and price they just need to step this up... Servers are slow, not very engaging, last time I got a drink 20 minutes after ordering it... unapologetically. They may have been overwhelmed but it's hurting their upscale vibe.
Best food, ambiance and wine😊

First time trying Georgian food and I wish it was everywhere! There is a restaurant area and bar area with full service. Even on a Wednesday night, the restaurant area was pretty full.  The ajaruli bread was easily the best thing ever. They mix the egg into the hot cheese at the table and everything gets cooked to perfection. Impossible to stop eating.  Plenty of other tapas-style options for vegetarians. They usually have a meat and vegetarian option for the soup dumplings- we tried the mushroom dumpling and they were amazing! The summer squash dressing was really good too. The only disappointing part was the dessert, which was a chocolate tort. Unfortunately they were out of the chef's special even though it was pretty early.  Would love to go back one day just for the ajaruli or to try their brunch menu.
Great Georgian food and good wine!

Much anticipated khachapuri but only boat shaped one tastes authentic. 15$ Eggplant appetizer and plates were okay, very little pieces of bread provided (one piece per adult). Unsure if last week Restaurant week was not available in the bar area but we were not offered the restaurant week menu... Bar service was slow and painful: waiter had to be waved for water, ordering meals, etc. Also, lots of mosquitoes INSIDE the bar. My friend got bitten 6 times on the legs and we overheard a dad make the comment  to the manager about mosquitoes which fell flat. Having been to Georgia we were looking forward so much to this experience - we were disappointed. Overall price affordable.

This might be the first time I’ve ever been in a restaurant with a mosquito problem. Our end of the table killed 8 of them with plenty more buzzing around. The manager said they were aware of the issue to which I can only wonder why it goes on. The more problematic issue is the cattle call way they delivered the food. We had a larger party and the server took orders from individuals. The food was delivered by a server walking up to the table and calling out a dish. This is lazy service and it implies we know the names of the dishes or what they should look like. We had never had Georgian food or been to this restaurant. The result was a whole table not getting what they asked for and feeling frustrated about it. The food as it was served was good, which is why the two stars. Had it been for service, it would have been one.
The food was meh. Everything sounded awesome but each of the dishes didn't quite jive.
Always looking for something different and interesting to eat.  Supra fit the bill. Delicious and unique.
Super Georgian restaurant. The service is great and food is delicious. I highly recommend their Khachapuri 😋. I also invite you to discover Georgian wine.
(Translated by Google) Very well. Recommend.  (Original) Sehr gut. Empfehle.
Food here is amazing and different, highly recommend

The food is amazing! I arrived 15 minutes before my reservation on a busy Friday night and they were still able to settle me immediately. Service was great as the waitress explained all their specials in details. Everything that we ordered tasted very good. I recommend you to try their amber wine! Overall I really enjoy eating here and will come back for sure to try other things on their menu.
Had a dinner with family here. Very unique experience. I liked the food, good selection of wine, great service too.
Excellent food and service.

Lit pricy but their food cost it. Love them for their Khachapuri and Khinkali. Good service, but if you sitting at the table, mostly, you waiting for your drink really long time. But I recommend it for everyone. You must to try Georgian food

We needed a late-night meal after a convention evening and this place was within walkable distance from the Washington convention center! The wait staff is amazing and know their food and alcohol pairings well! The food is great as well.  We ordered the dishes family-style, as they suggested, and we not disappointed as the dishes looked small, but were very filling and flavorful. Definitely give the egg bread and the soup dumplings a try! The meats are cooked just right. Parking may be hard, so look for the nearest metro station (Mt. Vernon Sq/ Convention Center area).
Seriously, everything you order at this place is just excellent.

Remarkable. I had very high expectations for the ajaruli khachapuri after having it in Russia a few years back and was not disappointed. I have come to Supra twice, and am consistently impressed by the quality of the food and service. The meat platter and khachapuri together are a great balance and will fill two hungry people easily. I would also recommend the khinkali, which are a whole new level of soup dumpling with a thicker skin and juicy filling. Supra satisfies my Georgian food craving every time and is on my list of top 5 favorite restaurants in DC.
Good stuff! Lamb sandwich is not impressive!

Outstanding place that deserves all the praise it has been getting. The experience was fantastic from the kind staff, to the lovely traditional hats displayed around the venue to the food/drink. The menu looks like a small plate kind of place. I’d say it’s more of a medium size plate place. The portions are fair sizes and very good. I loved the pork dumplings out of everything I tried. The chicken kabob is tasty and comes with four large chunks of meat. The chicken comes with two sauces on the side - the spicy sauce was my favorite. Try the wine flight for $17- comes with three portions to try. My friend and I had the amber wine flight. The wines were very nice and different compared to wines I’ve had in the USA. Come here and try Georgian food it’s amazing. The servers were helpful and came out frequently. They instructed us how/ when to eat some of the foods. It was an educational experience.  Second review- Date night or a place to take an adventurous eater. The food is amazing and you cannot go wrong with anything on the menu. I loved the orange wine. I wish I could buy more bottles to take home. The braised beef is a must. I would say get 3 dishes (1small, 1 bread type dish- the cheese egg one, and 1 big plate) and two people will be very comfortable. I loved the meat dumplings they were delicious.

We had tried Georgiann food before. The restaurant ambience is inviting, very nice decorated and the food is very good. We had the Supra sampler, Adjarian khachapuri, khinkali (dumplings), sausages. We took the wine suggested by the waiter and it was spectacular. Highly recommend Supra.
Deliciousness you can't find anywhere else! Very uniquely flavoured cuisine, and amazing wines. Just wish they had khinkali on the weekends too.
Amazing food! Took me right back to Batumi. Great service too!
Authentic Georgian food, a rare find in States. Staff knows their menu and it’s just like the Georgian tavernas all over the world.
Very good, very filling, and reasonably priced.
Great food and great service. Recommend.
Really good 👍 food and nice service

The food is awesome! It definitely lived up to the good reviews. The only thing that kept me from giving it 5 stars was the fact the we had to wait 25 minutes even though we had a reservation. And our waiter while nice, was not very attentive. With that being said, I would definitely go back.

One of my favorite restaurants in DC. The best khachapuri ajaruli in town. If you're not sure what that is, get it. It's a staple at any Georgian restaurant and is a must have. All of their food is delicious and cocktails equally so.
Great food. Excellent service. Really unique.

Delicious dinner, great service. The beef, chicken, lamb, and fish entrees were all excellent. Enjoyed the spreads for appetizers; the boat bread and dumplings were good but heavy. Delicious strawberry cake.
Amazing georgian restaraunt. the anjouli was to die for and the khenkali was nice and soupy.
Great food and excellent service. Our waiter was attentive and helpful.  Vegetarian friendly, lots of choices.
Amazing meal! You have to come for the once a month supra in the private room. Well worth the price to experience a true Georgian feast and make new friends!

Been here twice and loved both experiences.  I don't have much access to Georgian food so the uniqueness really appeals to me.  There are so many dishes that you really have to come back multiple times to try them all.  The small plates, the cold and hot dishes are all worth ordering.  Definitely go tapas family style to get the most of the visit. Also, if you like black licorice, you'll enjoy their soda.
Very delicious! I don't think I can describe how flavorful and perfectly cooked everything was. You just have to go and try it out yourself. I promise you there will be no regrets.

We have been here many times and always inside. Always had a good meal. Quality of ingredients seems high and their wine list is well balanced even being centered on the great Georgian wines. However, last visit was disappointing as we stayed outside. A good number of rats danced around the cart where they had the silvethere and that they use to serve outside. One waiter tried to 'scare' one of the rats but without any success. This tolerance is casting a bad shadow on the way in which hygienic conditions may be managed.
Everything here is so delicious!
Absolutely delicious food and wine.

Service was very very slow and rude. Waiter decided ge was going to put in our order in small parts, never asking us first. We were there for 2 hours never got last two dishes.  Waiter was very rude and unapologetic about it. Food is ok, but many dishes really lack flavor. Sulguni was too dry, eggplant missing a lot of flavor,  Khinkali which should hace been a star was awful by concent of all five of us, it tasted nothing like a real thing. Some dishes were still good, hachapuri was ok, djonjoli salad was good. Overall, it is an ok intro but not as good a Georgian food should be abd with the service really made it a negative experience.
Really good and unique foods. Works best as sort of a tapas-style dinner with a group. Get the khachapuri!
Very nice staff. Interesting food!

Incredible food, warm and unobtrusive service. Georgian food is heavy on breads and meats, and Supra nails the flavors (especially the condiments w/ heat)  I remember. Do NOT expect to eat on the cheap here, this is a full-flavor Georgian culinary experience. Try the wines, have brandy w/ desert. You won't regret it. Will come again.
Food was great, but service was terrible. Our waitress was completely inattentive. Unfortunate because the patio and the food were great, but poor service detracted from the experience.

It use to be good place... Year ago. But now it's just another horrible place. Seriously, if you're going to Georgian restaurant you expect delicious Georgian food. But not there. At first, portion size is really small. It's ok for French restaurant, but not Georgian. Second: in Georgian kitchen one of the most delicious dishes is kebob. It should be juicy, with special spices, cooked from a good marinaded meet and properly grilled. What we were served way too far from Georgian kebob. It was three pieces of burned charcoals called "kebob" by someone evil irony. I believe that Georgian chef left this restaurant. Real Georgian would die rather than serve such food to a guest. I'd not recommend this restaurant.

Great Georgian food and wine selections. Patio seating till 10pm, but get there by 830pm for outdoor seating as they cannot allow anyone to dine outside after 10. Great for large groups, large space indoors.
INCREDIBLE Georgian food-- very authentic and super delicious. Went here with some ladies from work several months back and I'm STILL dreaming about the ajaruli!
A sole Georgian restaurant in Washington. The courses are good and tasty. The restaurant has a long list of Georgian wines. Recommended.

Decent food, glad we tried this ethnic cuisine, but not blown away.  Eggplant Nigvzit: Best desh, wonderful taste combinations with the vegetable and walnut-space.  3 items in one dish.  Kupati: Beef/Pork sausage.  Was good, but didn't seem like anything special (could have gotten it at a Nats game).   Came with fennel and vegetables.  Ajaruli bread: Bread was fantastic, but it's almost like a soup bowl and in the middle they put egg, butter, and LOTS of cheese.  Was almost too cheesy and we ended up just eating the bread.   Decent dish, but would have liked more spices.  Khinkali (Beef) Dumplings: Just average.  Was bland and lacked any potent flavor.  Didn't really come with any sauce or sides.  Layout: Beautifully designed restaurant, ample space.  They have a cool map of Georgia and sell small trinkets.   There's an outdoor seating area which was popular.  Service: Easy to make and change reservations.  Wait staff was friendly, prompt, and very knowledgeable about the menu.
Delicious! And great, friendly service.
Food is really good but heavy. Soup dumplings and lamb dishes were my favorites.
Wonderful experience! Server was very knowledgeable about the different foods. Definitely recommend!!

The place is very nice. Sleek modern inside and has an outside patio. Several of the dishes are outstanding including cheese bread, dumpling and the salad. Avoid the pork kabobs. There were tough and don't have much flavor. The service was quick but the server who has unfriendly and when we complain about the pork he didn't he did not care. He does not mention that specials until I ask. Amber wine not worth paying for it. grape pudding tests ok.
Totally underwhelming. We were a group of 4 and all of us found the food pretty bland overall. Wouldn’t recommend or go back.
One of the best Khachapuri's I ever tried.

I made a reservation for Supra about a week and a half before I went, and even then the available times were very limited! When I arrived at 7:45PM on Friday, the restaurant was very full and I was very glad I made a reservation. The waiter came by to tell us about the menu, and we ended up sharing the rolled eggplant, baked mushrooms, and bread with cheese and spinach inside. Location and Parking: Interior style, funny Georgian hats, and plants are very appealing. Parking can be a bit difficult so we found an office building right across the Marriott and which closes at 9pm (didn't catch when but Wed for sure). If you plan to leave before then, I believe it's $12-$22 max.  Service was great.  Food - this is where I give it 3 stars and only because this is my opinion and taste preference. I understand that the style of food is Georgian with American influence. However, I believe the restaurant could still improve the food flavor to fit more flavor palates in this area. The appetizers were what we mainly liked. Entree just didn't make the cut. Presentation is nice though!  Liked - Eggplant Nigvzit - interesting taste and definitely enjoyable - Kartopili Kamit (Fingerling Potatoes) - cant go wrong with potatoes - Walnut Cake - awesome flavor and textures  Okay - Pork and Beef Soup Dumplings - more meatball flavor with a lighter/blander soup - probably to compensate for the meaty flavor and plus they give you pepper to add on. Dish just didn't have the zing I'm use to from Taiwanese soup dumplings so likely a fault from my previous expectation (so this is a dish you should judge for yourself).  Disliked - Chkmeruli (chicken in garlic sauce and traditional bread) chicken was well cooked - seasoned and moist. But the creamy garlic sauce was what made it underwhelming and weird. The texture is more like the consistency of porridge or egg drop soup. The sauce tasted very bland like it was missing salt and although the bread was good, it becomes useless without a great dipping sauce. However we did get half a chicken so maybe that's why there was less compensation of flavor in the sauce.  Conclusion - It seems the way the food is made is more dependent on the flavors from the meats while the sauce or soup is to add more moisture/ fluid texture? The sauce/ soup are missing salt which makes them bland. Based on other reviews and my experience, I wouldn't be confident that I would enjoy coming a 2nd time.

Cheese and bread galore! Supra is a fun culinary experience. My hubby and I had a Georgian feast with the tasting board, potato and cheese dumplings, and warm fluffy Khachapuri breads baked in a clay oven and filled with scrumptious cheese!  The $25 tasting board is fun to try and well worth it! The sampler of spreads, cheeses, breads, and eggplant rolls was a great way to dabble into the cuisine. The Eggplant Nigvzits stuffed eggplant rolls with walnuts and cilantro were hands-down my favorite item on the platter and quickly devoured! Of the Makho spreads, the carrot was surprisingly tasty and enjoyed the Nadughi soft cream cheese. The mozzarella like Sulguni cheese was my favorite, while my hubby enjoyed the guda cheese. Although I wasn't a fan of the minced veggie beet, spinach and green bean pkhali, it was nice to try them. The round cornbread was very dense, the rest of the bread basket was good. We ordered another round of bread which came with pesto aioli, it was so flavorful that I took some home!  The potato and cheese soup dumplings were quite tasty! The soft doughy shell with creamy filling and spices were delicious. We were so full from the sampler that we took some of the dumplings home. Surprisingly, they keep well and followed the Manager's advice to warm them up for a minute and a half covered with a damp paper towel to keep them moist in the microwave. It works, the dumplings were as good as new!  The standout dish of the night was the boat-shaped egg and cheese Ajaruli bread! It was fun to watch the waitress briskly stir in the egg and butter with the cheese. Voilà the egg was cooked and ready for consumption! It tasted like cheesy scrambled eggs in a fluffy bread bowl. The dish was loaded with rich savory guda, ricotta, and feta cheese (no Sulgoni). After a few bites, we threw in the towel! Sadly, the egg dish doesn't make for the best leftovers and ate just the fluffy crust at home.  If you enjoy stuffed cheesy bread, then definitely get the Megruli! The Megruli is like a rich white pizza loaded with Sulgoni and 3 other types of cheese. Megruli was good, but a bit too cheesy for me! After having just 1 slice, it was time for my hubby and I to pack up the rest. It makes for great leftovers over the next few days - just heat it up in the oven.  The citrus bubbly Bagrationi blossom cocktail was delicious! The St. Germain, Creme de Cassis and lemon balanced the dry sparkling wine and added a hint of sweetness. The Bagrationi Brut is a bit dry, and preferred the cocktail. My hubby enjoyed the seasonal beer.  My hubby and I were so stuffed that we didn't have room for dessert, (which is rare)! The cheese and breads are so rich and dense that next time we'll opt for just one flatbread and pepper in some hearty veggie dishes.  Great spot for groups to enjoy a Georgian feast and sample a variety of dishes. I recommend getting 2 dishes per person and 4-5 dishes are more than enough to share for a couple. We had plenty of leftovers! Excited to come go back for the dumplings and try the spinach and cheese Pkhlovani bread along with some potatoes, stews, and salads!

I think someone in my party had also ordered regular Lamb which we all tried and I can't even remember it, it was that forgettable (and I absolutely love lamb so I don't know how this is possible). The parking sucked as always in DC (but usually if parking is hard in a place you should accommodate some other way like not fit everyone so close together I could touch their face). The only good dish was their Turkish egg-and-cheese "pide". Their soup dumplings are without salt or sauce, just your ordinary dumpling. I've had better in cheap cafeterias run by Koreans or Chinese. I love Central Asian dumplings but this one was meh.
amazing food and perfect service; highly recommend
Great Georgian food and wine. A bit pricey and crowded but worth it for this very special cuisine!

The food was great, the decor was great, the staff was super friendly. We ordered lamb kabob, the cheese egg bread, salad and 6 soup dumplings. I told my husband that 3 dumplings would be enough but he insisted on 6. All of this food for just us two. The soup dumplings were by far my favorite. But they're huge- so get 3 and try other stuff!

This place is legit.  My wife is from Tbilisi so she knows her stuff and this is as close (save for her mother’s kitchen) as she said she has come to authentic Georgian food. The waitstaff was wonderful and the food was out of this world.  Will be coming back next time we’re in DC

Fantastic, authentic Georgian cuisine. If you've never been, ask your server for recommendations & prepare to enjoy! I also suggest getting the traditional Georgian wine. It's very different than what you'd find anywhere else and so, so good.
Great place to taste and learn of other cultures!
Food was excellent. Service was excellent. Price was very reasonable.  Highly recommend it.
My first visit and everything was delicious!
Excellent service and food choices for brunch. We did wine flight since we like Georgian red wines.

Wonderful Dining Experience! Enjoyed a lovely dinner at Supra. We started by reviewing an extensive Georgian wine list, ultimately settling on a semi-sweet, full-bodied, red wine called Kindzamauruli. Simply amazing!  For appetizers we tried 2 types of khachapuri -  imeruli and ajaruli. Both were delicious, but we especially liked the ajaruli, which was rich and buttery.  We also ordered the eggplant nigvzit, which was yummy, but not quite as satisfying as what I've eaten elsewhere...and at  $7/plate for three small pieces, way overpriced. We also tried the lobio kotanshi, which I'd never had before.  It was good, but not my personal favorite and not something I would probably order again. Warm kidney beans stewed with traditional spices and served alongside pickled cabbage and cornbread was a bit odd in taste and texture for this American palate.  For the main course, we tried the pork and beef kabobs, and chkmeruli (pieces of roasted chicken and traditional bread floating in a creamy garlic sauce). We enjoyed each of the dishes, but especially the pork kabobs. We heeded other diners comments about the meat being too dry, so specifically requested that the beef be prepared medium rare, and the pork not overcooked. Both kabobs came out perfectly; tender, hot and juicy.  And the chicken was nice and moist, with a robust garlic flavor. So we were very satisfied with everything that we ordered. Lastly, it's worth noting what exceptional service we received from Tanya, our waitress.  She was top notch; very attentive, helpful, and friendly... And really turned a great dining experience into a phenomenal one. We couldn't have been happier with our first visit to Supra and we'll definitely be back!
Expensive and definitely need a reservation, but the food is worth it!
Amazing and authentic
